[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] In computer science, the **segment tree** is a data structure used for storing information about intervals or segments.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] It allows querying which of the stored segments contain a given point.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] A similar data structure is the interval tree.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] A segment tree for a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage and can be built in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Segment trees support searching for all the intervals that contain a query point in time *O*(log *n* + *k*), *k* being the number of retrieved intervals or segments.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Applications of the segment tree are in the areas of computational geometry, geographic information systems and machine learning.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Let I be a set of intervals, or segments.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Let *p*1, *p*2, ..., *pm* be the list of distinct interval endpoints, sorted from left to right.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Consider the partitioning of the real line induced by those points.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] The regions of this partitioning are called *elementary intervals*.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] That is, the list of elementary intervals consists of open intervals between two consecutive endpoints *pi* and *p**i*+1, alternated with closed intervals consisting of a single endpoint.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Single points are treated themselves as intervals because the answer to a query is not necessarily the same at the interior of an elementary interval and its endpoints.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] A segment tree from the set of segments I, can be built as follows.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] First, the endpoints of the intervals in I are sorted.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] The elementary intervals are obtained from that.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Then, a balanced binary tree is built on the elementary intervals, and for each node *v* it is determined the interval Int(*v*) it represents.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] It remains to compute the canonical subsets for the nodes.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] To achieve this, the intervals in I are inserted one by one into the segment tree.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] The complete construction operation takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time, *n* being the number of segments in I.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Visiting every node takes constant time (assuming that canonical subsets are stored in a simple data structure like a linked list).
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] When we visit node *v*, we either store *X* at *v*, or Int(*v*) contains an endpoint of *X*.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] As proved above, an interval is stored at most twice at each level of the tree.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] There is also at most one node at every level whose corresponding interval contains *x*, and one node whose interval contains *x′*.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] So, at most four nodes per level are visited.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Since there are *O*(log *n*) levels, the total cost of the insertion is *O*(log *n*).
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] A query for a segment tree receives a point *qx*(should be one of the leaves of tree), and retrieves a list of all the segments stored which contain the point *qx*.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] In a segment tree that contains *n* intervals, those containing a given query point can be reported in *O*(log *n* + *k*) time, where *k* is the number of reported intervals.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] The query algorithm visits one node per level of the tree, so *O*(log *n*) nodes in total.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] On the other hand, at a node *v*, the segments in I are reported in *O*(1 + *kv*) time, where *kv* is the number of intervals at node *v*, reported.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] The sum of all the *kv* for all nodes *v* visited, is *k*, the number of reported segments.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] A segment tree *T* on a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage.
[src:persistent-segment-versioned/segment-tree] Let *v*1, *v*2, *v*3 be the three nodes at the same depth, numbered from left to right; and let p(*v*) be the parent node of any given node *v*.
